{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17495"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17495"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.95,0.03,0.03,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10185"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78661"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10185"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64004"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6683"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78661"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe arterial supply to the leg involves several major vessels that branch to provide blood to different compartments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the branching pattern of the major arteries in the leg?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bifurcates into anterior and posterior tibial arteries at the inferior border of the popliteus muscle","Divides into three separate vessels at the ankle joint","Continues as a single vessel into the dorsum of the foot","Branches into tibial vessels distal to the ankle","Divides into plantar arteries at the knee joint"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe popliteal artery \u003Cstrong\u003Ebifurcates into anterior and posterior tibial arteries at the inferior border of the popliteus muscle \u003C/strong\u003E(Image). The anterior tibial artery pierces the interosseous membrane to supply the anterior compartment and continues as the dorsalis pedis artery on the foot dorsum. The posterior tibial artery remains posterior and eventually forms the plantar arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDivides into three separate vessels at the ankle joint\u003C/strong\u003E - The main bifurcation occurs much higher at the popliteus muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinues as a single vessel into the dorsum of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - The vessel divides into two major branches well before reaching the foot\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches into tibial vessels distal to the ankle\u003C/strong\u003E - This branching occurs proximally at the popliteus muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDivides into plantar arteries at the knee joint\u003C/strong\u003E - The plantar arteries arise from the posterior tibial artery in the foot\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis branching pattern is essential for understanding lower limb vascular supply and clinical conditions affecting leg perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The popliteal artery bifurcates into anterior and posterior tibial arteries at the inferior border of the popliteus muscle.","The anterior tibial artery continues as the dorsalis pedis artery on the dorsum of the foot.","The posterior tibial artery 